%I A396978 #5 Jun 12 2026 09:23:12
%S A396978 1,1,1,4,48,3251,2093507
%N A396978 Number of unlabeled minimally 9-rigid graphs on n vertices.
%C A396978 A graph G is d-rigid, if every generic realization p in dimension d yields a framework (G,p) that is infinitesimally d-rigid; i.e., all its infinitesimal flexes are trivial. It is minimally d-rigid if it is d-rigid but looses this property upon deletion of any edge.
%C A396978 Every minimally 9-rigid graph with n>9 is (9,45)-sparse, that is every subgraph with n'>=9 vertices spans at most 9n'-45 edges. Minimally 9-rigid graphs have 9n-45 edges and hence are (9,45)-tight but not every (9,45)-tight graph is minimally 9-rigid.
%H A396978 Matteo Gallet, Georg Grasegger, Matthias Himmelmann and Jan Legerský, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3815171">PyRigi -- a general-purpose Python package for the rigidity and flexibility of bar-and-joint frameworks</a>, ACM Transactions on Mathematical Software, 2026.
%H A396978 Georg Grasegger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18548603">Dataset of minimally d-rigid graphs</a>, 2026.
%H A396978 Georg Grasegger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7457820">RigiComp - A Mathematica package for computational rigidity of graphs</a>, 2022.
%H A396978 PyRigi Developers, <a href="https://pyrigi.github.io/PyRigi/math/rigidity.html">Rigidity Theory</a>, 2025.
%H A396978 Walter Whiteley, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1090/conm/197">Some matroids from discrete applied geometry</a>, 1996.
%e A396978 The complete graphs on nine and ten vertices are minimally 9-rigid. So is the complete graph on eleven vertices with one edge removed. The three graphs that can be obtained from the previous one by adding a new vertex and connecting it to 9 of the existing vertices, are also minimally 9-rigid.
